Cognate_Comment: There is an interesting problem here: Tocantins Asurini has two words, /e-miat/ 'food; game' and /misat/, /misar-a/ 'deer'. Now, looking at the other words here, /e-miat/ is a better candidate for cognacy (especially if the /e-/ is, as I think it is, an independent morpheme marking alienable possession). But /misat/ is not a bad candidate either, and an /s/ is the normal development in Asurini of a PTG */j/ (*/mijat/ > /misat/ would be regular); and */mijat/ looks so close to /miat/ that I wonder if we don't have a case here in which a single PTG morpheme 'game, (meat) food)' split into two, /miat/ 'game, food' and /misat/ 'deer', with the /s/ < */j/ suggesting previous lexicalization. I'm not sure this is the case, and I don't have good arguments either way right now; but I think it's worth keeping in mind the possibility that /misat/ may be, or not be, the right cognate here. --SM

Cognate_Comment: In Magalhaes there is both jo'ok and ja'ok, the latter only in the context of the prefix a-; Tupinamba has /ok/ and /ja'ok/, where the former takes the jo- absolutive prefix. In Guaja this probably resulted in jo'ok and ja'ok, and then this was reanalyzed as part of the harmony system. We leave both forms in here as a result. Also, we interpret k-less versions of the root as a sort of allomorphy when there is no bound phonological material to the right -- ZJO

Cognate_Comment: This looks at first as though it could belong in TAKE.OUT~REMOVE2 (the "nosem" set), but... Mawe /h/: TG /s/ is in this case not a regular correspondence (only if there were an adjacent /i/), and there is no nasality in /hep/. The "true" cognate of TG /sem/ is Mawé /we~-tem/, which has a /t/, a final /n/, and nasality. So, for the time being at least, I prefer to see /hep/ as unrelated. -SM
